# Development Conventions

## Reusable Components

All UI components must be designed for reusability:

- **Props over hardcoding**: Accept props for content, variants, and behavior. Avoid hardcoded strings or styles inside components.
- **Composition**: Prefer composition (e.g. `children`, `render props`, slots) over rigid structures.
- **Single responsibility**: Each component should do one thing well.
- **TypeScript**: Export proper types for props. Use `React.ComponentProps`, `React.PropsWithChildren` where useful.

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD: Reusable, props-driven
export const Card = ({ title, children, className }: CardProps) => (
  <div className={cn('rounded-lg border p-4', className)}>
    <h3>{title}</h3>
    {children}
  </div>
);

// ❌ BAD: Hardcoded content
export const Card = () => (
  <div><h3>My Card</h3><p>Fixed content</p></div>
);
```

## Dummy Data in Constants

All dummy data, mock content, placeholder text, and static config must live in `src/constants/`:

- **Location**: `src/constants/` (group by feature, e.g. `home.ts`, `features.ts`).
- **Re-export**: Use `src/constants/index.ts` to re-export from submodules.
- **Imports**: Import from `@/constants` or `@/constants/home` (avoid inlining strings in components or pages).

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD
import { HOME_CONTENT } from '@/constants';
<p>{HOME_CONTENT.heading}</p>

// ❌ BAD
<p>Transforming Data into Insightful AI Solutions</p>
```

## File Organization

- `src/constants/` — All dummy data and static content
- `src/components/` — Reusable UI components (no dummy data inside)
- `src/templates/` — Page layouts and compositions
